{
  "text": "The modification of electrode surfaces with enzymes, such as with laccase and/or nanomaterials, could overcome these problems [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . However, selectivity of the enzymatic sensors destined for catecholamine determinations is limited because of high enzymes reactivity towards phenolic groups. Therefore, distinguishing the presence of dopamine over the presence of other catecholamine neurotransmitters while using enzyme based sensors, is very limited [CITATION_4] . More successful selectivity for the determination of dopamine in the presence of other neurotransmitters has been achieved by using sensors incorporated in the specific aptamer as a recognition element. The sensitivity of these sensors is, nonetheless, relatively low [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] .",
